<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos hookeri </i>ssp <i>. hookeri </i>is a prostrate to mounded, evergreen shrub that lacks a lignotuber. Seeds collect in the duff and ground in a seed bank as stones as plants age. Seeds germinate when heated. Plants can reproduce by layering. The relationships of the members of the <i>A. hookeri </i>complex, which include <i>A. montana </i>taxa, are complicated (Hickman 1993, Markos et al. 1998, Parker et al. 2012). This manzanita and ssp. <i>hearstiorum </i>with dark floral bracts are both CNPS list 1B.2 plants. This alliance is a component of the maritime chaparral (see maritime chaparral discussion in the Changes Since the First Edition section). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The alliance includes stands of ssp. <i>hookeri</i> in the Santa Cruz Mountains (Griffin 1978), the Pajaro Hills, and the Bureau of Land Management’s lands at Fort Ord Military Reservation on unproductive sandstone outcrops with sandy soils in Monterey and Santa Cruz Cos. (261Aj). Stands, such as those in the Prunedale Hills area (Davis 1972, Griffin 1978, Van Dyke et al. 2001) and the Elkhorn Slough area (CNPS 2006) include various levels of <i>A. crustacea, A. hookeri, A. montereyensis, A. pajaroensis</i>, and <i>A. tomentosa</i>. Further study will determine the differences between this alliance and <i>Arctostaphylos crustacea</i> alliance. This subspecies is also an understory plant in <i>Pinus radiata</i> and <i>Quercus agrifolia</i> stands. Plants of ssp. <i>hearstiorium</i>, which occur in coastal prairies in San Luis Obispo Co., represent special stands of maritime chaparral. We need more study to understand the role of this species in California’s maritime chaparral types. Stands in the Prunedale Hills have a historic fire cycle of 50 to 100 years, so Van Dyke et al. (2001) recommend prescribed burns in that interval. Infrequent fire may result in encroachment of trees and in shrub and seed bank declines. Tree encroachment will be slower than in other maritime chaparral types if the site has skeletal, oligotrophic soils (Davis 1972, Griffin 1978). On the contrary, frequent fire tends to convert the manzanita stands to coastal scrub or grassland. </div>
</div>

	

    
